2. How Verification Works (The Technical Path)
When a user submits this form, the protocol doesn't just "take their word for it." It runs a background check against the immutable history of the blockchain.
 * Immobility Check: The script queries the Legacy BTC Address. If the funds haven't moved in 5+ years, it adds a "Verified Stagnation" flag.
 * Signature Match: It checks the PGP Signature provided against the identity proof on file. If the PGP key was generated from the user's registered recovery email, the claim is approved.
 * The Minting Trigger: Once the üõ°Ô∏è Frost Security team approves the ticket, the restitution_logic.py script is executed, minting the equivalent value of FTC into the user's wallet as part of the next Migration Block.
3. Operational Best Practice (2026)
To prevent "Double-Claiming" (where someone tries to claim the same lost BTC twice), the protocol maintains a Restitution Nullifier Map. Once a legacy BTC address has been "repaid" in FTC, that address is permanently blacklisted from future claims in your ecosystem.
